You said:
vpc and subnet have 2 different cidr blocks


ChatGPT said:
Yes â€” and thatâ€™s exactly how itâ€™s supposed to be. Let me explain why:

âœ… Why VPC and Subnet Have Different CIDR Blocks
The VPC defines the entire IP address range for your virtual private network.

Each subnet inside the VPC must use a subset (a smaller CIDR block) of the VPCâ€™s CIDR block.

ğŸ“Œ Your Example
hcl
Copy
Edit
# VPC
cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/16"  # This gives 65,536 IPs

# Subnet
cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/24"  # This gives 256 IPs (subset of the VPC)
10.0.0.0/24 is inside the larger 10.0.0.0/16 range â€” so it's valid.

You can create many subnets in the same VPC, such as:

10.0.1.0/24

10.0.2.0/24

etc.

âŒ Invalid Case (for example)
hcl
Copy
Edit
# Subnet with CIDR outside the VPC â€” INVALID
